onential growth will plot as a straight line. Each major division is a factor of ten. This makes the slope of the plot the relative rate of change anywhere in the timeline, which allows comparison of one plot with the others throughout the pandemic.\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=700\n|height=400<!--height = 80 X <no. of log10 cycles in y axis>-->\n|colors=#FF6347,#FFC000,#87CEEB,#000000\n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|yAxisTitle=No. of cases\n|legend=Legend\n\n|x=31 Jan, ..., 11 Feb, 12 Feb, ...., 2 Mar, ....., 5 Mar, 6 Mar, 7 Mar, 8 Mar, 9 Mar, 10 Mar, 11 Mar, 12 Mar, 13 Mar, 14 Mar, 15 Mar, 16 Mar, 17 Mar, 18 Mar, 19 Mar, 20 Mar, 21 Mar, 22 Mar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr, 3 Apr, 4 Apr, 5 Apr, 6 Apr, 7 Apr, 8 Apr, 9 Apr, 10 Apr, 11 Apr, 12 Apr, 13 Apr, 14 Apr, 15 Apr, 16 Apr, 17 Apr\n\n|y1= 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 3, 3, 4, 10, 14, 17, 20, 20, 28, 34, 45, 59, 63, 93, 114, 147, 199, 253, 306, 367, 438, 495, 658, 840, 1036, 1264, 1534, 1836, 2337, 2777, 3548, 4149, 4731, 5389, 6343, 7497, 8672, 10131, 11917, 13584, 15770, 18328, 21102, 24490, 27938, 32008\n|y1Title=Confirmed \n\n|y2= 2, 2, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 7, 11, 14, 17, 17, 25, 31, 42, 56, 60, 89, 109, 142, 194, 241, 290, 351, 421, 473, 629, 799, 988, 1209, 1461, 1761, 2199, 2563, 3283, 3834, 4355, 4989, 5890, 6945, 8029, 9354, 11028, 12430, 14349, 16707, 19235, 22306, 25402, 29145\n|y2Title=Active \n\n|y3= , , 1, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 3, 3, 3, 3, 3, 3, 3, 3, 3, 3, 4, 5, 5, 5, 12, 16, 16, 17, 22, 29, 38, 45, 49, 64, 66, 121, 190, 235, 281, 333, 355, 406, 494, 580, 698, 795, 1045, 1291, 1470, 1694, 1986, 2304, 2590\n|y3Title=Recoveries\n\n|y4= , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , 2, 3, 4, 8, 9, 17, 24, 30, 34, 43, 45, 47, 58, 63, 76, 94, 106, 130, 148, 170, 198, 232, 273\n|y4Title=Deaths\n\n|yScaleType=log\n|yAxisMin = 1\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n